BACTERIAL CANKER, SWEET CHERRY - USA: (MICHIGAN)
************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 5 Jun 2012
Source: Interlochen Public Radio [edited]
http://ipr.interlochen.org/ipr-news-features/episode/canker-blasts-cherry-trees/2012-06-05-0


Canker blasts cherry trees
--------------------------
[Michigan's] sour cherry crop was basically wiped out by unusual spring weather. But perhaps worse than that, freezing weather injured sweet cherry trees so badly that a bacterial disease has taken a strong hold. And it will continue to do damage for years to come.

Bacterial canker usually gets into fruit trees where there's been a wound to the bark. But this [2012] spring numerous hard freezes killed buds and caused tiny injuries. And that allowed the bacteria to take hold like never before.

"I believe this year [2012] is significantly worse than anything I've seen," says a grower. What was unusual was that trees were stuck for weeks in their bloom phase. And that gave the canker plenty of time to kill parts of the tree that produce buds for next year. "And with the amount of bacterial canker infection today [trees are] never going to produce as well as they should for the rest of the life of that orchard," he says. He expects to see trees weakened and dying from this infection for several more years.

"There's some really beautiful orchards taken out by this disease," Nikki Rothwell, Horticultural Research Center, Northwest Michigan, says. She is documenting how much damage bacterial canker is doing. And she's trying out some sprays of nutrients that may bolster tree health and help to minimize the most severe effects.

Fruit trees are a 30 year investment. For 2012, the supply of Michigan sweet cherries will be way down and the price way up.

[byline: Bob Allen]

