[Bacterial canker of stone fruit is caused by 2 closely related species, _Pseudomonas syringae_ pv. _morsprunorum_, and _P. syringae_ pv. _syringae_. It is a serious disease of _Prunus_ crops, including sweet (_P. avium_) and sour cherry (_P. cerasus_). The disease affects stems and leaves. Symptoms may include sunken, dead areas of bark (cankers), which may girdle and kill off branches, gummy ooze, leaf necrosis, and brown spots on leaves and fruit.

Other pathovars (strains) in the _P. syringae_ group can affect a wide variety of plants, including crops such as kiwifruit, tomato, bean, maize, mango, soybean, and citrus. New diseases are emerging frequently and symptoms may include leaf specks, blights, and cankers.

The pathogens are spread by water, wind, mechanical means (including animal and human activities), and infected planting material. Disease management usually includes cultural practices, crop rotation, phytosanitation to prevent spread (for example, disinfection of pruning tools), and use of clean planting material. Chemical control (copper compounds, antibiotics) may be effective, but resistant strains have emerged for some pathovars. Varieties with different levels of resistance are available for some crops, including cherries.

